04798nam a22006135i 9781474472081DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20222002stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97814744720817 a10.1515/97814744720812doi  a(DE-B1597)615472  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 7aHIS0271302bisacsh1 aRoberts, John L, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Jacobite Wars :bScotland and the Military Campaigns of 1715 and 1745 /cJohn L Roberts. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tTHE AUTHOR -- tPREFACE -- tMAPS -- tChapter One ORIGINS OF THE JACOBITE MOVEMENT -- tChapter Two OUTBREAK OF THE 1715 REBELLION -- tChapter Three MARCH SOUTH TO PRESTON -- tChapter Four BATTLE OF SHERIFFMUIR -- tChapter Five END OF THE 1715 REBELLION -- tChapter Six JACOBITISM IN ECLIPSE -- tChapter Seven CHARLES EDWARD STUART ARRIVES IN SCOTLAND -- tChapter Eight MARCH SOUTH TO EDINBURGH -- tChapter Nine 'MASTERS OF SCOTLAND' -- tChapter Ten NEMESIS AT DERBY -- tChapter Eleven RETREAT TO SCOTLAND -- tChapter Twelve THE HIGHLAND CAMPAIGN -- tChapter Thirteen CONFRONTATION APPROACHES -- tChapter Fourteen BATTLE OF CULLODEN -- tChapter Fifteen AFTERMATH OF CULLODEN -- tChapter Sixteen ESCAPE OF THE PRINCE -- tSELECT BIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Jacobite Wars is a detailed exploration of the Jacobite military campaigns of 1715 and 1745, set against the background of Scottish political, religious and constitutional history.The author has written a clear and demythologised account of the military campaigns waged by the Jacobites against the Hanoverian monarchs. He draws on the work of recent historians who have come to emphasise the political significance of the rebellions (which had been dismissed by earlier historians), showing the danger faced by the Hanoverian regime during those years of political and religious turbulence.The Jacobite rebellions of 1715 and 1745 occurred within the context of the 1707 Act of Union, acquiring the trappings of a national crusade to restore Scotland's independence. James Edward Stuart promised consistently to break the Union between Scotland and England if he became King. The rebellions also had great religious significance: the Jacobite cause was committed to restoring a Catholic dynasty to the throne and was therefore supported by the small number of Catholics in the country, and also the Episcopalians, who were together set against the Presbyterians. The failure of the rebellions, culminating in the Battle of Culloden, coincided with the national identity of Scotland becoming associated with Presbyterianism and North Britain.John L. Roberts presents the view that the political vulnerability of Hanoverians would explain the strength of Government reaction to the 1745 rebellion, especially in the Scottish Highlands, and the ferocity of its retribution, which has long been lamented in popular Scottish culture.The Jacobite Wars will appeal to anyone with an interest in the military history of this key period in Scotland's past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 4aScottish Studies. 7aHISTORY / Military / Wars & Conflicts (Other).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311078046840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147447208140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474472081423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474472081/original  a978-3-11-078046-8  Edinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  